    "created_at": "2020-01-30T07:37:11Z",
    "updated_at": "2020-01-30T07:37:11Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Hmm, PCI compliance for fintech companies dictates a [minimum of 6 password attempts](https://www.securitymetrics.com/blog/pci-requirement-8-combatting-weak-passwords-and-usernames) before lock-out. \r\n\r\nEven if keycard is more analogous to a debit card, 3 attempts sounds a little restrictive, given that the user has to enter seed phrase or PUK code again to recover.\r\n\r\nPerhaps they could be warned about this before they get to their last attempt? In case they are traveling, for example, and can't access their means of recovery.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, we might consider simply freezing the account for 30 mins - 1 hour before user can try again, as a first measure. @andmironov @guylouis ",
