    "created_at": "2020-02-04T16:27:51Z",
    "updated_at": "2020-02-04T17:03:24Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> Additionally, we might consider simply freezing the account for 30 mins - 1 hour before user > can try again, as a first measure. @andmironov @guylouis\r\n\r\nthe lock down is done at the card level, and the card has no notion of time, so this not technically possible \r\n\r\n>Perhaps they could be warned about this before they get to their last attempt? In case they are traveling, for example, and can't access their means of recovery.\r\n\r\nthe number of attempts remaining can not be stored on the phone (simply because a card can be used by several phones), and this number of attempts is an info held by the card. For all interactions with one tap only (most of them are) we thus can't tell to the user in advance how many attempts he has left. It's actually super similar to how you use a debit card with ATM. You are (I have never been :) !) warned by the ATM about how many attempts I have left. However when the user makes a wrong PIN, we wan to warn him and tell him how many he has left. Detailed here https://github.com/status-im/status-react/issues/9347\r\n\r\n> Even if keycard is more analogous to a debit card, 3 attempts sounds a little restrictive, given that the user has to enter seed phrase or PUK code again to recover.\r\n\r\nThe setting to 3 max attempts is hardcoded for now in the applet, and the applet is installed at the factory. We could switch it to 6 in a new applet suite easily. Or make it a parameter of the initialization command. This second approach would be more elegant. I created a github issue https://github.com/status-im/status-keycard/issues/62",
